1 67.5420. 1. As used in this section, the following
2 terms shall mean:
3 (1) "Board", the board of directors appointed pursuant
4 to section 210.861;
5 (2) "Child care provider", any entity that is licensed
6 under section 210.221 and that provides early childhood
7 education services;
8 (3) "City", any city not within a county;
9 (4) "Early childhood education services", the same as
10 defined in section 161.244, which may include transportation
11 related to such services;
12 (5) "Early childhood education service provider", any
13 public school or charter school that is contracted with the
14 department of elementary and secondary education to provide
15 early childhood education services that adhere to the
16 quality standards as provided in section 161.213.
2

17 2. Notwithstanding any provision of law to the
18 contrary, all revenues generated by any tax imposed by a
19 city and approved by the voters for the purposes of
20 establishing an early childhood education and child care
21 services fund to improve the quality of, affordability of,
22 and access to early childhood development programs and child
23 care for children aged five years and younger shall be
24 deposited in the city treasury to the credit of a special
25 "Early Childhood Education and Child Care Fund" to
26 accomplish the purposes set out in this section and shall be
27 used for no other purpose.
28 3. The administrative control and management of the
29 funds in the early childhood education and child care fund
30 and all programs to be funded therefrom shall rest solely
31 with the board and shall be expended for early childhood
32 education services and child care services. The board shall
33 not be mandated to expend funds by an act of the general
34 assembly without a majority vote of the voters of the city.
35 The board shall use or disburse the funds in the early
36 childhood education and child care fund to provide and
37 administer programs improving the quality, affordability,
38 and access to early childhood development and child care
39 programs for children aged five years and younger. The
40 funds may be used for early childhood education services
41 provided by early childhood education service providers and
42 child care providers.
43 4. (1) The board may contract with any provider to
44 provide early childhood education services and child care
45 services and may place conditions on the use of such funds.
46 The board shall reserve the right to audit the expenditure
47 of any and all funds. The board may establish eligibility
48 standards for the receipt and use of such funds. No member
49 of the board shall serve on the governing body, have any
3

50 financial interest in, or be employed by any entity that is
51 a recipient of funds from the early childhood education and
52 child care fund.
53 (2) Funds expended by the board pursuant to this
54 section shall be expended in the following order of priority:
55 (a) For children in financial or familial need, as
56 determined by the board;
57 (b) For all other services provided pursuant to this
58 section.
59 (3) In addition to the priorities provided in
60 subdivision (2) of this subsection, a child care provider
61 shall prioritize the placement of children from families who
62 can document that they are on a waitlist for the department
63 of elementary and secondary education's child care subsidy
64 program.
65 5. The board shall only provide funding for early
66 childhood education services or child care services to
67 providers who serve children residing in the city.
68 6. The board may accept any gift of property or moneys
69 for the use and benefit of the persons to be served through
70 the programs established and funded under this section and
71 may sell or exchange any such property so long as such sale
72 or exchange is in the best interests of the programs
73 provided under this section and the proceeds from such sale
74 or exchange are used exclusively to fund such programs. The
75 board may solicit, accept, and expend grants from private or
76 public entities and enter into agreements to effectuate such
77 grants so long as the transaction is in the best interest of
78 the programs provided by the board and the proceeds are used
79 exclusively to fund such programs.
80 7. The provisions of subsections 3 to 6 of section
81 210.861 shall not apply to revenues deposited into the early
4

82 childhood education and child care fund and administered
83 pursuant to this subsection.
1 135.713. 1. Any taxpayer who makes a qualifying
2 contribution to an educational assistance organization after
3 August 28, 2021, may claim a credit against the tax
4 otherwise due under chapter 143, other than taxes withheld
5 under sections 143.191 to 143.265, and chapter 153 in an
6 amount equal to one hundred percent of the amount the
7 taxpayer contributed during the tax year for which the
8 credit is claimed. No taxpayer shall claim a credit
9 pursuant to sections 135.712 to 135.719 for any contribution
10 made by the taxpayer, or an agent of the taxpayer, on behalf
11 of the taxpayer's dependent or, in the case of a business
12 taxpayer, on behalf of the business's agent's dependent.
13 2. The amount of the tax credit claimed shall not
14 exceed fifty percent of the taxpayer's state tax liability
15 for the tax year for which the credit is claimed. The
16 [state treasurer] department of elementary and secondary
17 education shall certify the tax credit amount to the
18 taxpayer. A taxpayer may carry the credit forward to any of
19 his or her four subsequent tax years. All tax credits
20 authorized pursuant to the program shall not be transferred,
21 sold, or assigned, and are not refundable.
22 3. The cumulative amount of tax credits that may be
23 allocated to all taxpayers contributing to educational
24 assistance organizations in any one calendar year shall not
25 exceed a maximum of seventy-five million dollars. Such
26 maximum amount shall be annually adjusted by the [state
27 treasurer] department of elementary and secondary education
28 in an amount equal to the percent increase or decrease in
29 the amount of state aid distributed to school districts
30 pursuant to the provisions of section 163.031 in the current
31 fiscal year as compared to such amount in the preceding
5

32 fiscal year, rounded to the nearest thousandth. The [state
33 treasurer] department of elementary and secondary education
34 shall establish a procedure by which, from the beginning of
35 the calendar year until August first, the cumulative amount
36 of tax credits shall be allocated on a first-come, first-
37 served basis among all educational assistance
38 organizations. If an educational assistance organization
39 fails to use all, or some percentage to be determined by the
40 [state treasurer] department of elementary and secondary
41 education, of its allocated tax credits during this period,
42 the [state treasurer] department of elementary and secondary
43 education may reallocate these unused tax credits to those
44 educational assistance organizations that have used all, or
45 some percentage to be determined by the [state treasurer]
46 department of elementary and secondary education, of their
47 allocated tax credits during this period. The [state
48 treasurer] department of elementary and secondary education
49 may establish more than one period and reallocate more than
50 once during each calendar year. The [state treasurer]
51 department of elementary and secondary education shall
52 establish the procedure described in this subsection in such
53 a manner as to ensure that taxpayers can claim all the tax
54 credits possible up to the cumulative amount of tax credits
55 available for the calendar year.
56 4. A taxpayer who makes a contribution to an education
57 assistance organization shall not designate the student who
58 will receive a scholarship grant.
59 5. The provisions of sections 135.712 to 135.719 and
60 sections 166.700 to 166.720 shall be effective in any fiscal
61 year immediately after any fiscal year in which the amount
62 appropriated for pupil transportation pursuant to section
63 163.161 equals or exceeds forty percent of the projected
64 amount necessary to fully fund transportation aid funding
6

65 for fiscal year 2021. If the amount appropriated for
66 transportation pursuant to section 163.161 in any succeeding
67 year falls below such amount, no additional scholarships for
68 newly qualified students shall be awarded.
1 135.714. 1. Each educational assistance organization
2 shall:
3 (1) Notify the [state treasurer] department of
4 elementary and secondary education of such organization's
5 intent to provide scholarship accounts to qualified students;
6 (2) Demonstrate to the [state treasurer] department of
7 elementary and secondary education that such organization is
8 exempt from federal income tax under Section 501(c)(3) of
