25

17 charges tuition for the rendering of elementary or secondary
18 educational services;
19 (7) "Program", the same meaning as used in section
20 135.712;
21 (8) "Qualified school", an FPE school or any of the
22 following entities that is incorporated in Missouri and that
23 does not discriminate on the basis of race, color, or
24 national origin:
25 (a) A charter school as defined in section 160.400;
26 (b) A private school;
27 (c) A public school as defined in section 160.011; or
28 (d) A public or private virtual school;
29 (9) "Qualified student", any elementary or secondary
30 school student who is a resident of this state, who is not
31 an illegal alien, and who:
32 (a) Has an approved "individualized education plan"
33 (IEP) developed under the federal Individuals with
34 Disabilities Education Act (IDEA), 20 U.S.C. Section 1400 et
35 seq., as amended, in accordance with rules of the state
36 board of education or with the applicable rules of another
37 state, or who has been diagnosed with dyslexia, as the term
38 "dyslexia" is defined in section 633.420, by a licensed or
39 state-certified professional who is qualified by training
40 and experience to diagnose dyslexia and who is acting within
41 such professional's lawful scope of practice; or who has
42 received a diagnosis of a disability from a physician who is
43 licensed under chapter 334, a psychologist who is licensed
44 under chapter 337, or a mental health professional as
45 defined in section 632.005, while acting within such
46 individual's lawful scope of practice; or who has received a
47 diagnosis of a disability from a physician who holds an
48 active license issued by another state or territory of the
26

49 United States, the District of Columbia, or the Commonwealth
50 of Puerto Rico; or
51 (b) Is a member of a household whose total annual
52 income does not exceed an amount equal to three hundred
53 percent of the income standard used to qualify for free and
54 reduced price lunches, and that meets at least one of the
55 following qualifications:
56 a. Attended a public school as a full-time student for
57 at least one semester during the previous twelve months;
58 b. Is a child who is eligible to begin kindergarten or
59 first grade under sections 160.051 to 160.055; or
60 c. Is a sibling of a qualified student who received a
61 scholarship grant in the previous school year and will
62 receive a scholarship grant in the current school year.
1 166.705. 1. A parent of a qualified student may
2 establish a Missouri empowerment scholarship account for the
3 student by entering into a written agreement with an
4 educational assistance organization. The agreement shall
5 provide that:
6 (1) The qualified student shall enroll in a qualified
7 school and receive an education in at least the subjects of
8 English language arts, mathematics, social studies, and
9 science;
10 (2) Except for a qualified student who is in the
11 custody of the state, the qualified student shall not be
12 enrolled in a public school operated by, or a charter school
13 located within, the qualified student's district of
14 residence and shall release the district of residence from
15 all obligations to educate the qualified student while the
16 qualified student is enrolled in the program. This
17 subdivision shall not be construed to relieve the student's
18 district of residence from the obligation to conduct an
19 evaluation for disabilities;
27

20 (3) The qualified student shall receive a grant, in
21 the form of moneys deposited in accordance with section
22 135.714, in the qualified student's Missouri empowerment
23 scholarship account;
24 (4) The moneys deposited in the qualified student's
25 Missouri empowerment scholarship account shall be used only
26 for the following expenses of the qualified student:
27 (a) Tuition or fees at a qualified school;
28 (b) Textbooks required by a qualified school;
29 (c) Educational therapies or services from a licensed
30 or accredited practitioner or provider including, but not
31 limited to, licensed or accredited paraprofessionals or
32 educational aides;
33 (d) Tutoring services;
34 (e) Curriculum;
35 (f) Tuition or fees for a private virtual school;
36 (g) Fees for a nationally standardized norm-referenced
37 achievement test, advanced placement examinations,
38 international baccalaureate examinations, or any
39 examinations related to college or university admission;
40 (h) Fees for management of the Missouri empowerment
41 scholarship account by firms selected by the educational
42 assistance organization;
43 (i) Services provided by a public school including,
44 but not limited to, individual classes and extracurricular
45 programs;
46 (j) Computer hardware or other technological devices
47 that are used to help meet the qualified student's
48 educational needs and that are approved by an educational
49 assistance organization;
50 (k) Fees for summer education programs and specialized
51 after-school education programs;
28

52 (l) Transportation costs for mileage to and from a
53 qualified school; and
54 (5) Moneys deposited in the qualified student's
55 Missouri empowerment scholarship account shall not be used
56 for the following:
57 (a) Consumable educational supplies including, but not
58 limited to, paper, pens, pencils, or markers;
59 (b) Tuition at a private school located outside of the
60 state of Missouri; and
61 (c) Payments or reimbursements to any person related
62 within the third degree of consanguinity or affinity to a
63 qualified student.
64 2. Missouri empowerment scholarship accounts are
65 renewable on an annual basis upon request of the parent of a
66 qualified student. Notwithstanding any changes to the
67 qualified student's multidisciplinary evaluation team plan,
68 a student who has previously qualified for a Missouri
69 empowerment scholarship account shall remain eligible to
70 apply for renewal until the student completes high school
71 and submits scores to the [state treasurer] department of
72 elementary and secondary education from a nationally
73 standardized norm-referenced achievement test, advanced
74 placement examination, international baccalaureate
75 examination, or any examination related to college or
76 university admission purchased with Missouri empowerment
77 scholarship account funds.
78 3. A signed agreement under this section shall satisfy
79 the compulsory school attendance requirements of section
80 167.031.
81 4. A qualified school or a provider of services
82 purchased under this section shall not share, refund, or
83 rebate any Missouri empowerment scholarship account moneys
84 with the parent or qualified student in any manner.
29

85 5. If a qualified student withdraws from the program
86 by enrolling in a school other than a qualified school or is
87 disqualified from the program under the provisions of
88 section 166.710, the qualified student's Missouri
89 empowerment scholarship account shall be closed and any
90 remaining funds shall be returned to the educational
91 assistance organization for redistribution to other
92 qualified students. Under such circumstances, the
93 obligation to provide an education for such student shall
94 transfer back to the student's district of residence.
95 6. Any funds remaining in a qualified student's
96 Missouri empowerment scholarship account at the end of a
97 school year shall remain in the account and shall not be
98 returned to the educational assistance organization. Any
99 funds remaining in a qualified student's Missouri
100 empowerment scholarship account upon graduation from a
101 qualified school shall be returned to the educational
102 assistance organization for redistribution to other
103 qualified students.
104 7. Moneys received under sections 166.700 to 166.720
105 shall not constitute Missouri taxable income to the parent
106 of the qualified student.
